[2] UK Regions
Medway
------
Date: Mon 10 Jun 2013
Source: Kent online [edited]
http://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway_messenger/news/Measles-cases-on-the-rise-1779/


There have been 14 cases of measles across the region since the start of the year and a total of 962 cases in England. This continues the trend seen since early 2012, with monthly totals around the highest recorded levels seen since 1994. There was one case in Medway in April 2013, and one in March 2013, compared with none at all in 2012.

The MMR catch-up programme, run by Public Health England, NHS England, the Department of Health, and local authorities, aims to prevent measles outbreaks by giving MMR to as many unvaccinated and partially vaccinated 10-16 year olds as possible in time for the next school year. Medway GP practices have been contacting the families of patients aged 10 to 16 who have missed out on the MMR jab.

Lancashire
----------
Date: Thu 13 Jun 2013
Source: The Lancashire Telegraph [edited]
http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/health/10483902.Vaccination_call_to_East_Lancashire_parents_after_measles_cases/


New figures show there were 3 confirmed measles cases in Pendle in April 2013, as health officials continue a catch-up vaccination campaign for youngsters. There were 5 other cases in the rest of Lancashire and Cumbria in April 2013, but none of these were reported in East Lancashire. Since the start of the year [2013], there have been 73 confirmed cases across the region, though an outbreak in the Lancaster district accounted for 52 of those. A national catch-up programme is aiming to prevent measles outbreaks by giving MMR to as many unvaccinated and partially vaccinated 10-16 year olds as possible. This age group is most at risk of measles due to the fall in coverage of MMR that occurred in the late 1990s and early 2000s, when concern around the discredited link between autism and the vaccine was widespread.

