******
[4] Pakistan (Islamabad)
Date: Mon 10 Jun 2013
Source: Pakistan Daily Times [edited]
http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2013%5C06%5C10%5Cstory_10-6-2013_pg11_5


After Sindh and Punjab, the capital and its rural areas are under the threat of a measles epidemic. According to hospital sources, around 40 measles patients, almost all of them children, are brought to the Polyclinic Hospital and Pakistan Institute of Medical Sciences (PIMS) of the federal capital everyday. The Polyclinic Hospital spokesman, Dr Sharif Astori, said that 15 to 20 measles-affected children were brought to the OPD [outpatients department] of the hospital and provided treatment, though no patient has been admitted. The doctor said that the disease had not become an epidemic so far. On the other hand, the PIMS Hospital spokesman, Dr Waseem Khawaja said that dozens of measles patients were brought to the OPD of the hospital daily and provided proper treatment. He said that a few children were admitted who were later discharged after recovery.

