The Americas
------------
[7] Argentina (ex Spain)
Date: Wed 12 Jun 2013
Source: Epidemiological Report Cordoba [in Spanish, machine trans. edited]
http://www.vetcomunicaciones.com.ar/page/articulos/id/135/title/Reporte-Epidemiológico-de-Córdoba.-Argentina


On 12 Jun 2013, the National Health Surveillance reported a highly probable case of measles (IgM positive) in Buenos Aires. The patient is a 43 year old immunocompromised male recently arrived from Spain. He entered the country 2 months ago and developed fever and upper airway congestion on 1 Jun 2013 and was treated by a private physician. On 5 Jun 2013, he was admitted to a private hospital suffering from high fever, nasal discharge, and a skin rash. Initial examination excluded measles or rubella. Further examination and case control measures were initiated and diagnostic samples submitted to a reference laboratory [presumably providing the IgM-positive result].

During 2011, 1310 cases of measles were reported throughout the Americas and designated imported cases or import-related cases. Most importations originated from Europe with lesser numbers from elsewhere.

In 2012, the Region of the Americas has recorded outbreaks of imported and import-related cases of measles totalling 135 cases. About 90 per cent of these cases were reported by the United States and Ecuador, with 54 and 68 cases, respectively.

